,Not Recommended,246300,21949753,"Posted: 20 March, 2016",all,The Horror Network | Embalmer,"Paranormal is a first person, ""found footage"" style game where you play as artist Mattel Clarke. Mattel has been witnessing strange events in his house, and has come to believe it is haunted. In an attempt to capture his findings, he sets up video cameras all around his house and utilizes a handheld camera for capturing POV shots.Now, Paranormal was one of the first games that I ever bought on Steam. Back in 2012, the game looked promising and interesting, and I also had no concept of ""Early Access"" since I was new to PC gaming. Back then, the game had significantly less content than it does now... however, it has also been in Early Access for almost five years. There is only one guy working on the game, which is why the development process is taking an excruciatingly long time. On the flip side, after almost five years, you would expect a game of this caliber to be nearing completion; on the contrary, Paranormal is far from it.Instead of finishing the game as it was, and then working on an upgraded version, the developer decided to put the entire project on hold while he transferred the content to Unreal Engine 4. In the base game, you walk around and try to trigger paranormal events. Once your camera battery is nearly drained, you head back to bed and see the cameras set up around the house; you're able to flick through them in an attempt to catch more spooky activity. Once you wake again, usually something, or rather multiple things, in the house has changed. You rinse and repeat the process until you come to an ending. It took a solid year for anything more than one or two endings to be added, and initially Paranormal was only about 10-20 minutes long, per playthrough.Now, the newly added portion of the game is all done in Unreal 4. It has awesome visuals, great voice-overs, it's set prior to the events in the base game, and it supposedly has some pretty cool paranormal events. Unfortunately, I couldn't get that far in my play of the new content for one reason; the head bobbing is so atrocious that I seriously felt like I was going to be ill. I'm not a person who gets motion sickness at all, but I seriously had to stop playing after about 10 minutes. If this is taken out, or at least made an optional feature, I feel that the experience for some people would be a lot better. Likewise, there is still some optimization that needs to be looked at, as I did find my framerate fluctuating between 40-60 quite consistently.The reason that I cannot recommend Paranormal at this time is, to be quite honest, I personally feel like we will never see the finished product. The developer has a lot of work to do by himself, and he has a busy life that draws him away from working on the game quite often. There's great potential to be had here, and I'm extremely hopeful that one day there will be a finished product. Until I see this game nearing release, with more of the content tied together, I can't give this one a thumbs up. If you don't mind investing in Early Access titles that are going to take a long, long time to come to fruition, go ahead and pick it up. Otherwise, just hold off for a while. I'll be updating this review at various intervals of the games lifespan, however there has been no update for over half a year at this time.Rating:3.0/5.0- Average, can take it or leave it.The Horror NetworkCurator|GroupClick for Gore"
76561198014729953,Recommended,246300,10026730,"Posted: 5 May, 2014",all,The_Dubester,"When I first started playing Paranormal, I was instantly reminded of the Paranormal Activity film. You are the protaganist who is investigating the hauntings of his new residence using a camcorder. You have to walk around the house to pick up any unusual activity (believe me there is a lot!!!) and rest every now and again to ""charge"" the recorder. As you play through the game you are gradually introduced to the story of what had happened in the house with a host of jump scares to keep you busy. Playing this game alone and with headphones is highly recommended to get the full effect of the this ghost simulator and I can guarantee at least one spine tingling moment. It is a game where both the seen and unseen can play tricks with your mind."
,Not Recommended,246300,7798537,"Posted: 27 November, 2013",all,BC_Animus,"This early access explorational horror game has a lot of potential, with its promise of dynamic random gameplay; upcoming direct-X 11 graphics; and even future Oculus Rift support.  However at this current stage of development I find the game to be rather basic and generic, with its limited gameplay, controls, writing, and even audio and visuals.Unfortunately the biggest let down for me was the horror part of Paranormal. Perhaps it is just a case of me having been desensitised by years of playing survival horror games, but I find the scares on offer here to be rather dull – they are all just too clichéd and expected, with your usual “ghost appearing in the mirror for a second” and “water turning bloody” type fares.  Overall the game has left me unfrightened, and to be honest unimpressed."
,Recommended,246300,10039595,"Posted: 6 May, 2014",all,Pointnclickster,"Maybe this is just me, but I find that I get more satisfaction from Indie titles nowadays. I remember greenlighting this way back thinking that it looked interesting. First of all, I find playing an Early Access game exciting. You get to watch a game be developed and in a way help it to be better. Now the gameplay. If you like movies like Paranormal Activity or The Blair Witch Project then you will enjoy it. Yes, you could call this game a gigantic cliche, but the developer loves the material so much that it is almost a reminder of why we love to be creeped out by this kind of stuff. As said, the game is a work in project. Graphics are dated (personally I like it that way) and will be updated, new content is being worked on, and the story is getting more fleshed out, but what is available now is worth playing. I am looking forward to watching this game come full circle."
