,Not Recommended,246300,10025168,"Posted: 5 May, 2014",all,Kuehnau,"In 'Paranormal' you play as an artist who has rented their own personal studio where they can work on their art without being disturbed. But then you start to notice you may not be alone in the studio, no one believes you, so you decide to try and collect 'evidence'.You don't actually collect evidence, but the developer uses it as an excuse to make your point of view through a fuzzy, crappy, pixelated video recorder that no one should have any business owning in 2015.The entire game involves you wandering around your studio, trying to find proof the house is haunted. As you spend more time in the studio, you'll find little tidbits of information that help you slowly understand the haunting and the story behind it.The studio is crampt and small, making exploring the house a very short affair. What is supposed to attract you is all of the paranormal activity happening in the studio.The game boasts re-play-ability by having 'randomly generated' events happen. The issue is, after the first or second play through, there isn't really anything random about it, the events that happen are so few and varied you may very well start seeing the same thing happen during the first play through.Obviously, since this game is in Early Access, it's unpolished. But I wouldn't even use that word with this title. The last time I played it, the game had parts of game play elements that were scrapped, but never removed, the game had two title screens, one of which doesn't work or save any of your options properly.If you want to believe what the author says on the game's forums here, you'd be lead to believe not only has he fixed several bugs, added in new content and added in a demo for the Unreal Engine 4 remake, but I didn't see any of that. Why? Because right after the title screen the game locks up every, single time.This isn't an issue of my hardware, I got a great set-up that plays current gen titles just fine. The issue is with the developer, his programming and his progress with the title. At this point, I just consider this lost money. If the author reads this, I wouldn't mind you buying a game for me from my wish list to make up for the worthless garbage you sold me."
